article.description: Golden State capped its best month in more than 13 years with a 113-106 victory over Sacramento.
article.headline: Warriors wins 11 in Nov. for first time since 1974-75
article.linkText: Richardson, Davis lead Warriors past Kings
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Kings didn't have reason to pay much attention to the Golden State Warriors in recent years. While the Kings were focused on topping the Lakers, Spurs and other Western Conference powers, their northern California neighbors were in the midst of a playoff drought that has stretched back more than a decade. That's what made the capper to Golden State's best month in more than 13 years so satisfying to the Warriors. Jason Richardson scored a season-high 33 points and Baron Davis added 25 and 16 assists to lead Golden State past Sacramento 113-106 Wednesday night. "This was a statement game," Richardson said. "I look at it as a rivalry. They're up north, an hour away from us. They used to whoop on us. It was like a big brother thing the last couple of years. We now know that it's changing around." This marked the first meeting between the two teams since March 10, 1996, when the Warriors have a better record than the Kings (7-8). The tide started shifting after Davis joined the Warriors last February, and Golden State beat Sacramento twice in a week span in March to win the season series. Now they're showing that the strong finish Davis fueled last season wasn't an aberration. The Warriors (11-6), off to their best start since winning 12 of their first 17 games in 1991-92, had their winningest month since March 1992 and won 11 games in November for the first time since their championship season in 1974-75. "I think we're off to a good start. But that's what it is -- a start," said Mike Dunleavy, who scored 19, including a clutch 3-pointer in the final minute. "We're on the right track. We have a winning record, we're at the top of our division, but it's only a start." Troy Murphy (14 points, 10 rebounds) and Adonal Foyle (10 points, 13 rebounds) each had double-doubles for Golden State, which won its fourth straight game. Bonzi Well scored 23, Shareef Abdur-Rahim and Mike Bibby added 22 apiece and Brad Miller had 20 for the Kings, who couldn't overcome a 5:35 stretch without a field goal in the third quarter. "They have a nice team," Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "I think they're learning how to win. That's important. They had some success early and it's probably carrying over for them." Sacramento tried to fight back in the fourth quarter. Bibby hit a drive and a 3-pointer on successive possessions to cut the Warriors' lead to 100-94 with just over 3 minutes left. After Davis missed a jumper in the lane as the shot clock ran down, the Kings had a chance to cut it even further but Abdur-Rahim was called for traveling with 2:38 to go. Dunleavy then hit two free throws on the other end. After a three-point play by Abdur-Rahim cut it to 103-99, Dunleavy hit a 3-pointer to put it away with just under a minute left. "He's made some big shots for us," Warriors coach Mike Montgomery said. "We made plays at the end of the game when you have to make plays." Sacramento had no answer for Richardson, who scored on dunks, drives and long jumpers in his latest big game against the Kings. Richardson is averaging 29.8 points in his last eight games against the Kings. The Warriors took control in the third quarter with a 13-1 run, featuring an alley-oop pass from Richardson to Davis that made it 72-63. Derek Fisher followed with a 3-pointer to give Golden State its first double-digit lead of the game and Richardson's baseline jumper capped the spurt and made it 78-64 with 3:36 to play in the third. Sacramento answered with eight straight points before Davis scored four in the final minute of the quarter, including a 3-pointer with 5.8 seconds left to make it 82-72. Davis, who came into the game shooting 24 percent on 3-pointers, was 6-for-12 from long range to go along with his season high in assists. "He can penetrate, he handles the ball well and sees the open guys," Abdur-Rahim said. "He got his shot going tonight and when he does that, he's real tough." Richardson scored 15 points in the first quarter -- the most by a Golden State player in any quarter this season -- and the teams were tied at 31 after 1.

Game notes
It took Golden State 29 games to win 11 games last season. ... Bibby had scored 25 or more points in five straight game. ... The Kings beat the Warriors 102-88 on March 10, 1996, to improve to 26-33 and drop Golden State's record to 28-34. ... Miller, who came into the game with three 3-pointers, hit two in the third quarter. He also had seven assists.
